        <body>
            <div type="edition" xml:lang="tam-Latn" rendition="class:tamil maturity:vernacular">
                
                <ab>
                    <lb n="1"/>
                    <hi rend="grantha">śrī</hi>
                </ab> 
                
                <p>
                    Ik-kāl
                    <lb n="2"/>ceyvittā
                    <lb n="3" break="no"/>n koṭumpā
                    <lb n="4" break="no"/>ḷūṟ kaikkō
                    <lb n="5" break="no"/>ḷa<choice><orig>n</orig><reg>ṉ</reg></choice> ceṭṭi kam
                    <lb n="6" break="no"/>pa<choice><orig>n</orig><reg>ṉ</reg></choice>-ā<choice><orig>n</orig><reg>ṉ</reg></choice>a caṉanāta A
                    <lb n="7" break="no"/>ṇukka-pallava
                    <lb n="8" break="no"/>raiya<choice><orig>n</orig><reg>ṉ</reg></choice> <g type="pc">.</g>
                </p>
                
            </div>
            
            <div type="apparatus">
                <listApp>
                    <app loc="0">
                        <lem></lem>
                        <rdg source="bib:SrinivasaRao1979_01"></rdg>
                    </app>
                    
                </listApp>
            </div>
            
            <div type="translation" resp="part:emfr">
                <p n="1">Fortune!</p>
                <p n="1-8">
                    He who had this stone<note>That is, the pillar on which the inscription is engraved.</note> made
                    <supplied reason="subaudible">is</supplied>
                    Cananāta<note>Sanskrit Jananātha.</note> Anukka Pallavaraiyaṉ
                    <hi rend="italic">alias</hi>
                    Ceṭṭu Kampaṉ, a <foreign>kaikkōlaṉ</foreign> from Koṭumpālur.
                </p>
            </div>
            
            <div type="commentary">
                <p>It is not clear if the same pillar also bears another inscription recording the gift of the pillar by another individual (<ref target="DHARMA_INSKotumpalur00045"/>). If so, it would seem that two different individuals donated the pillar.</p>
            </div>
            
